{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"A file placed inside a subdirectory of the watched root is processed, not only files placed directly in the root directory.","required_reality_check_level":"System","justification":"This behavior depends on real filesystem watcher behavior for nested paths and proving an external side effect (the file is actually processed/end result appears). A mock watcher can hide recursive-watch and path normalization failures. Not Agentic/Workflow because no AI/ML decision is involved.","test_description":"Run the daemon against a real temporary watched directory, create a nested subdirectory, write a file inside it, and assert via round-trip readback in the output directory (or observable processing artifact) that exactly that nested file was processed.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.76,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The deduplication logic correctly discards a second processing request for the same file path within a configurable time window.","required_reality_check_level":"Integration","justification":"The risk is module handoff (event intake -> dedup window state -> pipeline scheduler), so unit-only is insufficient. Real OS/network/subprocess is not explicitly required by this behavior text, and correctness does not depend on AI output; therefore System/Agentic/Workflow are disqualified.","test_description":"Wire real in-process components (ingest + dedup + scheduler) with a controllable clock, submit two requests for the same path within the configured window, and assert only one pipeline execution occurs; then submit after window expiry and assert execution occurs again.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When the operating system emits multiple filesystem events for a single file write, the daemon processes the file exactly once.","required_reality_check_level":"System","justification":"The behavior explicitly names OS-emitted duplicate filesystem events; this is real infrastructure and can differ from fakes. You must prove externally visible exactly-once processing via round-trip observation. Not Agentic/Workflow because no model decisions are involved.","test_description":"With the daemon running on a real watched directory, perform a write pattern known to generate multiple events (e.g., temp-write + rename/append), then assert only one processing result appears for that file (single output artifact or single recorded completion).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.07,"System":0.9,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"If the watched directory is removed and then recreated while the daemon is running, the daemon resumes watching the new directory without a restart.","required_reality_check_level":"System","justification":"Directory deletion/recreation while a watcher is active is OS/filesystem lifecycle behavior. The test must show external side effect after recreation (new file gets processed) via real readback. Not Agentic/Workflow because no AI/ML sequence exists.","test_description":"Start daemon on a real directory, remove that directory, recreate it at the same path, then place a new file and verify it is processed without restarting the daemon (confirmed by output artifact/logged completion).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.09,"System":0.88,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When multiple files arrive at the same time, they are processed in the order determined by their creation timestamps.","required_reality_check_level":"System","justification":"Ordering here depends on filesystem metadata/event timing and must be validated through externally observable processing order. In-process mocks can miss timestamp resolution and event-delivery realities. Not Agentic/Workflow because no model output quality or multi-agentic chain is involved.","test_description":"Using a real watched directory, create multiple files in a tight window with controlled creation times, run daemon, and verify observed processing completion order matches creation-timestamp order from real filesystem stat data.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.34,"System":0.58,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"A file that is still being written to when the arrival event fires is not picked up for processing until writing is complete.","required_reality_check_level":"System","justification":"This is a real filesystem timing/partial-write condition; mocks often hide file lock/flush/rename timing issues. The success criterion is an external side effect after completion (processed output only once file is complete). Not Agentic/Workflow because no AI/ML decision-making is present.","test_description":"Start daemon on a real directory, write a file in chunks with delays (keeping it incomplete during initial event), assert no processing output appears while writes are ongoing, then close/finish write and assert processing occurs afterward with complete content.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.11,"System":0.86,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
